Exploring health with 2015 Victorian local government areas (LGA) statistical profiles

Introduction

An exploratory data analysis to find correlation between segments of the Victorian population and issues concerning health

  • Potential predictors that cause ill health.

  • Identify in which areas these issues occur

  • Discuss possible solutions to health problems which may reduce health costs

The data

Data collected by the Department of Health and Human services from local governemt areas that cover population, housing, health statuses and many other metrics. 79 total LGAs.

https://www2.health.vic.gov.au/about/reporting-planning-data/gis-and-planning-products/geographical-profiles

  • 404 variables

  • 80 rows in total

  • Excel sheet with tabs that divide the data by LGA, Area, Region and division

  • Using ‘LGA’ tab of the original excel file

Pre-processing

  • Each tab of interest was converted to a csv file for easy analysis in R

  • Combined data with Victorian spatial data for map visualisation (https://www.data.vic.gov.au/data/dataset/vicmap-lite)

  • Many of the variables that are meant to represent numerical figures were cleaned and converted to numeric fields

  • LGA Name field cleaned for merging with spatial data

Factors affecting health and health costs:

  • Social housing
  • Low income families with children
  • Low proficiency in English
  • Level of education

Social housing

  • There is a medium correlation between Social housing residency and increased notifications of Chlamydia

  • Both are more highly correlated with high crime areas

Social housing area breakdown

Low income families with children

  • Low income families could be perceived to have heavy financial burdens

  • Possibly leads to health taking a lower priority

Low income families with children (contd.)

  • Strong negative correlation between lower income families indicates lack of private health insurance

  • Positive correlation between low income families and delaying health consultations

Low income families with children area breakdown

Low profeciency in English

  • Possible signal of immigrants and people new to the country

  • They might have a harder time knowing how to access health services

  • Potentially lack of vaccination programs in the country they came from

Low proficiency in English area breakdown

Level of education

  • A correlation between people not having finished year 12 and being treated for preventable health issues

  • This could be seen as a factor that is increasing the cost of healthcare

  • If issues can be prevented before they need hospitalisation, the government could potentially provide more facilties for issues that are not preventable

People who did not complete year 12 area breakdown

Conclusion and Discussion

What are some ideas to mitigate these health concerns

  • Social housing:
    • Free contraceptive vending machine inside of social dwellings
    • Simple awareness, in the form of an event around the social dwellings
  • Low income families
    • Conduct further in-depth surveys to see what health issues are people unable to solve
    • Use survey results to extend eligibility criteria of people who can be bulk billed
    • Delay payment for immediate consultation (interest free)
  • English Proficiency
    • Community engagement to help new comers in knowing how to access services
    • Provide free or subsidiesed vaccines
  • Education
    • Increase awareness in how to identitfy and prevent medical issues before hospitalisation is needed
